data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt` calls to address.

Your code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):
You could simplify with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, token) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, token);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This is purely a modernization choice — not a migration requirement.
